32:35Z", "closed_at": null, "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR", "body_html": "<p>Currently, if the model has one input only (excluding the parameters), then the user needs to set requires_grad=True for backwards to work. This is needed because checkpointing function is an autograd function with no learnable parameters itself. In general, users shouldn't need to set requires_grad=True for the models written using pytorch modules.</p>\n<p>proper way to handle this is not known yet.</p>", "body_text": "Currently, if the model has one input only (excluding the parameters), then the user needs to set requires_grad=True for backwards to work. This is needed because checkpointing function is an autograd function with no learnable parameters itself. In general, users shouldn't need to set requires_grad=True for the models written using pytorch modules.\nproper way to handle this is not known yet.", "body": "Currently, if the model has one input only (excluding the parameters), then the user needs to set requires_grad=True for backwards to work. This is needed because checkpointing function is an autograd function with no learnable parameters itself. In general, users shouldn't need to set requires_grad=True for the models written using pytorch modules. \r\n\r\nproper way to handle this is not known yet. "}